text.text: A Guide to Archway

Just up the road from Arsenal’s Emirates Stadium, this pocket of North London is positively swimming with the red and white shirts of gooners. Archway is pretty much Highgate’s scruffy little brother: kind of rough around the edges, a bit ASBO-y at times, but generally that loveable rogue from childhood tales of good and bad. Go on then Archway ya rascal, let’s have it large!
Best for… bikes and burgers

tip.text:
It might look like a pub from the outside, but The Spoke is modelled more on its name than its appearance: a bike cafe (in an old pub). Bicycles are of course welcome, but you’ll find a fair few human beings here too - it’s a cosy hangout stocking great coffee (Union), loose-leaf teas (Brew Tea Co.) and local craft beers.

The kitchen here is absolutely something to shout about; Archway local and cafe regular Juan is all over the pork shoulder sandwich with pickles (“messy in a good way”), while the burgers are stuff of local folklore. Curious? They serve breakfast until 4pm along with your classic Bloody Marys, so you know this is your new Sunday hangout spot after a long cycle through the long, arduous streets of London.

text.html: It might sound odd, a bike cafe in an old pub and all, but we haven’t got anything against 'odd' at Dojo, and there’s a definite charm about this hangout. Giles Coren (The Times food critic) reckons The Spoke “serves the best burgers in north London”. If that’s not a big shout then we don’t know what is, and we’d highly recommend the best way of verifying any such claim: in person. Hells yeah.

Best for... buying things

tip.text:
Every Saturday, a short stretch of Holloway Road comes to life with this awesome market where you can get your foodie needs met by independent, local traders. They’ve got all the basics, from fresh fruit and veg and free-range meat to cheese and charcuterie – um yes, charcuterie is totally a basic.

Alongside these, you can find stalls hawking global grub like Trinidadian jerk chicken, Greek spanakopita, and Georgian stuffed cheesy bread (!), plus coffee and pastries. While you’re at it, browse through the books at ‘Word on the Street’ and check out African textiles and custom carpentry. The perfect Saturday afternoon.

They’ve got all the basics, from fresh fruit and veg and free-range meat to cheese and charcuterie – um yes, charcuterie is totally a basic. They're also dishing out global grub like Trinidadian jerk chicken, Greek spanakopita, and Georgian stuffed cheesy bread. The perfect Saturday afternoon, really.
Best for… art and craft (beer)

tip.text:
Artist Nic Sharpe has owned this plot for some 18 years now, but a recent refurbishment turned St John’s Tavern into what it is today: a large, incredibly stylish, somewhat minimalist space, part-pub part-restaurant. If you’re here for the boozing then expect heaps of local craft, including Hammerton’s N7 Pale Ale (from down the road), along with a bit of great value nosh from the bar’s tapas kitchen.

The restaurant dishes oour British classics (incl. a smashing Sunday roast), sourcing produce locally and changing the menu on a seasonal basis. We’re also big fans of the weekly collab with local wine merchants Theatre of Wine - it’s BYOB in the restaurant on Mondays, so cop a bottle and get on down.

text.text: Tapas bar, craft beer boozer, stylish restaurant... St John’s Tavern ain’t messin’. They do the lot in here: homemade scotch eggs the size of your firstborn, their own cured meats, brown sauce made on-site, and puffy pork crackers that look more like a cloud than anything else (they get a whole pig in every week and use every inch of the thing for something tasty). This place is really worth a gander.
Best for… breathtaking views, breathtaking gradients

tip.text:
Rubbing shoulders with the legendary Highgate Cemetery, Waterlow Park has all the peaks and valleys required to rob you of your breath for two reasons: 1) it can be decently steep, and 2) the views from the top are spectacular. What’s more romantic than watching a pink sun catch the metal and glass of London’s skyline at dusk?

If all the hiking (it’s really not that steep) and duck-feeding leaves you a tad peckish, there’s a cheeky cafe in a lovely, walled garden at the top of the park - ideal for filling your beak. Ample benches, much greenery and friendly dog-walkers only add to the appeal of this lovely open space.

text.text: Depending on which entrance you opt for, Waterlow Park might well fall under either Archway or Highgate’s jurisdiction - we’ve gone for Archway, and sincerely apologise for any offence caused. What’s up? Rolling hills, ducks in a pond, stunning skyline views and a playground for the young'uns - that’s what. You can even grab a bite and a hot bev up top in the pop up version of the currently closed Lauderdale Restaurant. Very handy.
Best for… cheap ‘n’ cheerful chow

tip.text:
Graceful in its simplicity, and considerably more attractive than its neighbours, this spot is an understandable favourite of local residents and workers. You can expect great value delights in Hot Wok ranging from the stalwart that is Thai Green Curry to the immensely popular Singapore Laksa (and everything in between, which is lots).

We’re big fans of the traditional Chinese door (from the pre-lock days that required cunning assembly to secure goods) and matching kung-fu bench - simple additions to an understated interior. If you’re keen enough to feel the need to take something home, why not peruse the shelves stocked with cooking ingredients and teas?

text.text: The Far East is arguably responsible for some of the best food this good planet has to offer, and while the cuisine of each nation is well-nuanced and unique, serving them all up in one place is very much on the cards (in our humble opinion). Hot Wok Kitchen is a Pan-Asian paradise at the top of Holloway Road - it’s pretty understated in here, but the prices are real kind to the ol’ pockets.
Best for… beaming baristas and quality coffee

tip.text:
Everyone in Archway loves Bread and Bean. Huge windows allow for oceans of natural light - perfect for remote working and photosynthesising alike, the Union coffee is properly delish, while the trained and infectiously-friendly baristas will have a smile on your face in no time.

Impressed by fancy contraptions and unorthodox techniques? Get an aeropress coffee and experience all the subtleties of flavour in those beans, be they Ethiopian or Columbian. If you’ve got a rumbling tum then there’s no need to panic, you can tuck into the likes of eggs benedict and fish finger sandwiches with homemade tartare sauce up in here - that’s what’s up.

text.text: Bread and Bean might just be the jewel in Archway’s crown - pretty much everyone we spoke to while we were having it large named it as one of their favourite local spots, and it’s easy to see why. Union supply these guys with some of the best coffee in town, while the staff are just outrageously friendly, chatty and up for a laugh. Working outta the office? This is the place.
Best for… surrendering all control and embracing the unknown (mystery tapas)

tip.text:
Indecisiveness and menu fuss are completely removed from the equation at Del Parc, where the only thing you need to worry about is giving them your dietary requirements when you book a table. What do you eat? Well, expert chef Steven Morrish will see to that, taking you on a creative and tasty foodie journey through Spain and North Africa.

This isn’t traditional tapas - they prefer the term sharing plates - but you may well see the likes of Galician mussels, Moroccan lamb meatballs or black tiger prawns with chilli, garlic, white wine and lemon. Then again, you might not - it’s all guesswork really, which we think is pretty exciting. All wines come from the Iberian Peninsular, which makes for apt drinking in Del Parc.

text.text: We’re all “have a bit of this, have a bit of that,” so obviously tapas is well up our street. It seems ours isn’t the only street, since Junction Road has this delightful little spot in its ranks. You don’t get to choose what you eat (you just tell ‘em what you physically can’t), but who needs agency when you’ve got a bona fide pro looking to give you a culinary experience to write home about?
Best for… seasonal suppers and sacred spirits

tip.text:
This charming pub has its roots well and truly planted in the community: the menu consists of dishes made with local, market produce and changes on a daily basis in accordance with what’s available and in-season. Whether it’s ice cream, fish, meat or cheese, absolutely everything used here comes from local suppliers.

Thirsty? Well, you’re in luck, this independent pub only dabbles in the finest liquids: cask ales rotate, spirits come from Sacred and the wine list is curated to promise an eclectic mix. It’s not all food and drink here though, with an all-you-can-eat moules marinieres and fries night on Wednesdays, a film club every other Tuesday and Bluegrass nights every first Monday of the month. It’s all going down.

text.text: With the ongoing, rapid gentrification we see popping off left, right and centre, we’re kinda big fans of the local renaissance visible in certain corners of the capital. Sure, it’s easy to get stuff online or from Tesco, but if you actually want “every little” to “help,” then there’s nothing better than supporting the markets and businesses in your area. The Star is all about that, so we’re all about The Star. Rant over.
Best for… a sneaky sushi stop-off

tip.text:
Yes, Sushi Wa looks somewhat unspectacular from the outside, but step into this slick Japanese restaurant and find out why locals are keen to get involved. The lighting is low and ambient, while partial tree trunks climbing out of miniature pebble gardens add to the feeling of Japanese calm - all that’s missing is a running water soundtrack.

Busy on weekends and not without decent midweek lunchtime custom, you could build your own meal with classics like maki rolls, teriyaki dishes and gyoza, or partake in one of Sushi Wa’s many special set menus (£11 - £20) and let the experts do the choosing. Asahis and sake all round if you care for authenticity. Takeaway and delivery available for you couch potatoes out there.

text.text: Maybe checking out those ducks in Waterlow Park made you hungry, maybe it was the hills, or maybe you’re just one of those people that eats food most days of the week. Whichever category you fall into, you’ll be glad to know there’s a lovely Japanese restaurant halfway up Highgate Hill - we’ll admit that it looks average at best from the outside, but the inside is pretty damn cool and the food is tasty. Curious? Go on, investigate.
